<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
	<!--
		================================================================================
		App Sandbox — ENABLED (Phase 2, 2026)
		================================================================================
		All ~/searxng-local file I/O and docker CLI spawning now routes through the
		SearxlyDockerHelper XPC service (no sandbox), so the main app can be sandboxed.

		Hardened Runtime is also enabled.
	-->

	<!-- App Sandbox (Phase 2: all ~/searxng-local I/O routes through SearxlyDockerHelper XPC service) -->
	<key>com.apple.security.app-sandbox</key>
	<true/>

	<!-- Network access for WKWebView and HTTP probes -->
	<key>com.apple.security.network.client</key>
	<true/>

	<!-- Downloads folder: used by downloadDockerDesktopIfNeededAndPrepare() to save Docker.dmg -->
	<key>com.apple.security.files.downloads.read-write</key>
	<true/>

	<!--
		=== NETWORK EXTENSIONS (for real WireGuard VPN / Packet Tunnel Provider) ===

		This capability is what allows the app to start a real system-wide full-tunnel
		WireGuard connection via the separate SearxlyWireGuardTunnel extension target.

		Because this project is being prepared for open source (not yet publicly released),
		the COMPLETE / PRODUCTION configuration is documented here so that anyone looking
		at the source can see exactly what a working paid-team setup looks like.

		Current state (for the developer's personal team):
		- The key is commented out below so the project builds and runs on a free
		  personal Apple ID team without provisioning profile errors.
		- The entire VPN UI, pill (top-left), popovers, config management, fake
		  "connect", status, browser button, demo warnings, etc. continue to work fully.
		- Real routing is not possible on a personal team (Apple limitation).

		Full production version (uncomment this block when you have a paid Apple
		Developer membership + a provisioning profile that includes the capability):
	-->
	<!--
	<key>com.apple.developer.networking.networkextension</key>
	<array>
		<string>packet-tunnel-provider</string>
	</array>
	-->
	<!-- <key>com.apple.developer.system-extension.install</key> <true/> -->

	<!--
		See VPN/IMPLEMENTATION_NOTES.md (the big "Critical: Signing / Team / Capability
		Requirements" section right at the top) + the SearxlyWireGuardTunnel/ folder
		for the complete instructions, support files (Info.plist + entitlements for
		the extension), and how to create the target.
	-->

	<!-- Required for good JavaScript performance and modern site rendering (YouTube, etc.) -->
	<key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit</key>
	<true/>

	<!-- Helps with modern web features and some network-related operations in WebContent -->
	<key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory</key>
	<true/>

	<!-- Allows the WebContent process to read network configuration (directly addresses the networkd plist warnings) -->
	<key>com.apple.security.temporary-exception.files.absolute-path.read-write</key>
	<array>
		<string>/Library/Preferences/com.apple.networkd.plist</string>
	</array>

	<!-- Broad temporary exceptions so WebContent can reach system services -->
	<key>com.apple.security.temporary-exception.mach-lookup.global-name</key>
	<array>
		<string>com.apple.runningboard</string>
		<string>com.apple.pboard</string>
		<string>com.apple.lsd</string>
		<string>com.apple.launchservices</string>
		<string>com.apple.coreservices</string>
		<string>com.apple.CoreServices.coreservicesd</string>
		<string>com.apple.audio.AudioComponentRegistrar</string>
		<!-- Additional for media / audio / video in WebContent processes (helps with "WebKit Media Playback" and audio registrar issues) -->
		<string>com.apple.coremedia</string>
		<string>com.apple.audio.audiohald</string>
		<string>com.apple.media</string>
		<string>com.apple.avfoundation</string>
		<string>com.apple.mediaplayer</string>
		<string>com.apple.audio.toolbox</string>
		<string>com.apple.coreaudio</string>
		<string>com.apple.CARenderServer</string>
		<string>com.apple.mediaremoted</string>
		<!-- Extra services hit in Xcode 27 beta / macOS 27 WebContent sandbox violations (from console logs) -->
		<string>com.apple.tccd</string>
		<string>com.apple.tccd.system</string>
		<string>com.apple.iconservices</string>
		<string>com.apple.iconservices.store</string>
	</array>

	<!--
		NOTE: We cannot add the private entitlements that the WebContent logs repeatedly request:
		  com.apple.runningboard.assertions.webkit
		  com.apple.multitasking.systemappassertions
		They cause exactly this provisioning error with automatic signing.
		These are required for full "WebKit Media Playback" RBS assertions in the sandboxed
		WebContent processes. Without them, YouTube (and other heavy video sites) often fail
		to initialize the decoder / audio session even if our adblock JS is a complete no-op.

		All other mitigations below are applied to make videos work as much as possible.
	-->

	<!--
		NOTE on "WebKit Media Playback" / RunningBoard assertion errors:
		The logs showed many:
		  "Failed to acquire RBS assertion 'WebKit Media Playback'"
		  "originator doesn't have entitlement com.apple.runningboard.assertions.webkit"
		  etc.

		Those specific entitlements (com.apple.runningboard.assertions.webkit,
		com.apple.multitasking.systemappassertions, com.apple.private.allow-explicit-graphics-priority)
		are private/internal and cannot be used with automatic signing / standard
		developer profiles. Xcode will refuse to provision (exactly the error you got).

		We keep the mach-lookup temporary exceptions (above) which can help some
		WebContent <-> system service connections (pboard, audio, launchservices, runningboard, etc.).

		Real fixes for video have to come from the WebView configuration + adblock JS side
		(we have already relaxed network blocks for YT, stopped forcing styles on <video>
		elements themselves, changed media gesture requirement to .audio, removed src=''
		nuking on unload, etc.).
	-->

	<!--
		XCODE 27 BETA / WWDC26 WEBKIT + LOCAL AI CRASH NOTES (2026-06)
		===========================================================
		Console shows repeated WebContent deaths:
		  - CRASHSTRING: rdar://problem/28724618 Couldn't connect to launchservicesd.
		  - Sandbox restriction (159) on pboard, coreservicesd, AudioComponentRegistrar, tccd (TCCAccessRequest kTCCServiceListenEvent)
		  - "kLSServerConnectionStatusProcessIsDaemonMask is set"
		  - networkd plist sandbox, FSNode/IOKit failures, "invalid product id '(null)'"
		  - ViewBridge to RemoteViewService Terminated (Code=18)
		  - NSHostingView reentrant layout warnings (directly tied to Local AI chat send)

		Root causes observed when "send a prompt" in Local AI Chat:
		1. LocalAIChatSheet + custom .overlay (ZStack + spring transition) + inner ScrollViewReader +
		   streaming per-token (or coalesced) @State mutations + .onChange + withAnimation(proxy.scrollTo) +
		   conditional tool cards / follow-up chips / attachment chips + suggestions background Tasks
		   = massive layout thrashing while the view is being laid out.
		2. The main window is a complex hybrid (WKWebViews everywhere via WebViewContainer/Representable +
		   NSHostingView for the SwiftUI ContentView/Root). Dying WebContent processes + ViewBridge
		   terminations make the hosting view extremely sensitive to reentrant layout from the AI overlay.
		3. Even with App Sandbox = NO + Hardened Runtime + the temporary-exception.mach-lookup list,
		   Xcode 27 beta WebKit (WebContent XPC services) is stricter about what child renderers can
		   reach. Many of the failing services (especially full launchservicesd / coreservicesd behavior,
		   and private RunningBoard assertions) require entitlements that are either:
		     - Private (com.apple.runningboard.assertions.webkit etc.) → provisioning failure on auto-sign
		     - Or only fully effective when the *main* app bundle declares App Sandbox + a matching
		       provisioning profile that propagates the exceptions to the WebContent bootstrap.

		TCC kTCCServiceListenEvent ("Input Monitoring" in Privacy & Security) requests from WebContent
		are surprising but appeared in the logs. If the app starts prompting the user for it, or if
		WebContent stays broken, try granting "Input Monitoring" to Searxly in System Settings.
		(We added com.apple.tccd / tccd.system to the mach-lookup list above as a best-effort.)

		What we did:
		- Added a few more services seen in the 27-beta logs.
		- (Critical) Made Local AI send/stream/scroll/tool-dismissal paths use DispatchQueue.main.async
		  for *all* @State mutations and proxy.scrollTo that happen during/after prompt generation.
		  Coalesce small streaming deltas. Removed withAnimation from the hot paths.
		- This should stop the "send prompt → reentrant warnings → ViewBridge death → crash/unstable"
		  cascade even while the underlying WebContent sandbox spam continues.

		Longer term options (documented for when you have a paid team + custom profile):
		- Turn App Sandbox back on (ENABLE_APP_SANDBOX=YES) + add the full set of WebKit-friendly
		  exceptions + com.apple.security.device.audio-input etc. if needed. Test Docker/local SearXNG
		  paths carefully (they currently require the main process to be unsandboxed or have explicit
		  user-selected folder access + XPC for docker CLI).
		- Or keep unsandboxed but embed a small XPC service whose only job is to host WKWebViews
		  (gives the WebContent processes a different (less daemon-like) bootstrap environment).
		- File feedbacks with Apple on the rdar and the "WebContent in hardened+unsandboxed app on 27"
		  behavior; include the exact CRASHSTRING lines.

		While iterating on 27 beta: use the built-in "Copy full Local AI diagnostics" button in
		Settings → Local AI. It includes prompt versions, prefs, RAG state, recent actions, and
		instructions to also paste filtered Xcode console ([LocalAI] + the WebContent / NSHostingView lines).

		Unrelated but visible in your log: Docker socket errors are from LocalSearxngManager
		(~/searxng-local docker-compose). Only relevant if you are testing the one-click local
		SearXNG feature; they do not affect the on-device Apple Intelligence path.
	-->
</dict>
</plist>